owest delay weapon be primary in a dualwield</span><hr size=1> The primary hand does not need to attack to enable a Dual Wield check. It is purely based on the delay of the weapon in the hand...you could have a fishing pole in the primary hand and your offhand will still attack.<br><br>There seem to have been a lot of misinformation floating around on the subject lately, so I decided to prove this by using a Shimmering Partizan (piercing, 39 delay) in the primary hand and a Lamentation (slashing, 19 delay) in the offhand and logging the fight. This excerpt illustrates it quite well: <br><br>[Mon Feb 11 14:53:24 2002] You pierce A Stonegrabber for 48 points of damage. <br>[Mon Feb 11 14:53:25 2002] You try to kick A Stonegrabber, but miss! <br>[Mon Feb 11 14:53:25 2002] You slash A Stonegrabber for 15 points of damage. <br>[Mon Feb 11 14:53:25 2002] You slash A Stonegrabber for 33 points of damage. <br>[Mon Feb 11 14:53:25 2002] A Stonegrabber smashes YOU for 96 points of damage. <br>[Mon Feb 11 14:53:26 2002] You try to slash A Stonegrabber, but miss! <br>[Mon Feb 11 14:53:26 2002] You slash A Stonegrabber for 14 points of damage. <br>[Mon Feb 11 14:53:27 2002] You pierce A Stonegrabber for 25 points of damage. <br>[Mon Feb 11 14:53:27 2002] You pierce A Stonegrabber for 25 points of damage. <br><br>Notice how the offhand clearly slashes at two separate times between primary-hand pierces.<br><br>Generally speaking, having the faster weapon in the primary hand is the better idea due to the bonus that is applied to every attack, but if your best primary weapon is slower than the offhand (ie. Wurmslayer), your offhand won't lose any attacks because of it. <p>Dahnlor Wiffingblade<BR>Level 60 Half Elf Warlord<BR>The Kindred - Drinal<BR><I>...and they cowered in fear for what had so nearly come to pass!</I><BR></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#2F2F4F><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub14.ezboard.com/ushelrabbi.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Shelrabbi</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>knows that Warriors are Superior</span><br>  Posts: 91<br> <font color=#FF0000>(2/25/02 8:08:12 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub14.ezboard.com/fthesteelwarriorthearena.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1162.topic&index=13>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.steelwarrior.org/forum/p_atk.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Should the lowest delay weapon be primary in a dualwield</span><hr size=1> Sorry, I'm really high right now, so I didn't read the posts before mine. I'm just gonna answer the main post.<br><br>What he's saying is that you will only swing your offhand when you swing your mainhand (untrue). BUT if the delay on your offhand hasn't recycled yet, then you won't swing the offhand no matter what. So say you have a 16 delay weapon in your offhand, and a 15 delay weapon in your main hand. You swing the mainhand, then it checks the offhand and passes, so you swing the offhand. Next round comes and you swing the main hand again. Then there is the check for the offhand, but the result of this check doesn't matter cause you haven't recycled the delay on your offhand. So now you have to wait another 15 delay to have a chance to swing your offhand again. In this scenario, you would either want an offhand with equal to or less delay then your mainhand OR a very high damage offhand with double the delay. Now this is all wrong however, so there is no reason to pay any attention to it, this is just what the guy was saying.<br><br>And to clarify, the reason you put the fastest weapon in the mainhand is cause every time you hit you get a damage bonus. The more times you hit, the more automatic damage you get. <p>Shelrabbi Hassida<BR>Tallon Zek<BR><BR>"Your love of the halfling leaf has dimmed your wits."</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A H